# Intentionally no rules. Cloudflare Pages serves real files in this deploy
# directly; anything not on disk falls through to Pages' native 404.
#
# Do NOT add a catch-all SPA rewrite (`/* /index.html 200`). This app has no
# client-side router — `/` is the only HTML entry, and about.html / changelog.html
# / support.html are real files — so a path that isn't on disk genuinely doesn't
# exist and should 404. A catch-all is actively harmful here: when an installed
# PWA still points at an old /assets/index-<oldhash>.js after a redeploy (the
# hash rotates every build), the catch-all answers that dead URL with index.html
# as text/html + HTTP 200. The browser then tries to evaluate HTML as an ES
# module, fails to parse, and renders a blank white page — turning a recoverable
# "stale asset, reload me" into a silent brick.
#
# A previous version tried to force misses to 404 with lines like
# `/assets/* /index.html 404`. Cloudflare Pages only honours 200/301/302/303/
# 307/308 statuses in _redirects, so those 404 rules were silently dropped and
# every miss fell through to the catch-all anyway. Removing the catch-all lets
# Pages' built-in 404 handle misses correctly (a real 404, so a stale-asset
# request fails loudly instead of being fed HTML).
